    en: "Public Health Law Article 27-F (Sections 2780 through 2787) gives HIV-related information stricter confidentiality than ordinary medical records. A healthcare provider, laboratory, insurer, or government agency may not disclose HIV testing information without specific written authorization from the person tested, except in narrow statutory exceptions. The authorization required for HIV disclosure is separate from and more detailed than a general HIPAA release. Unlawful disclosure can trigger civil and criminal penalties. Anonymous testing is available at public health department clinics — the person's name is never recorded. A positive result triggers partner notification assistance but the original patient's identity can remain anonymous to partners."
